codex
The allocator has no direct `m_previous` writes outside `Block::setPrevious`; 
`addToFreeList`/`removeFromFreeList` only touch the tree links in `FreeBlock`. The suspicious 
divergence is that those tree links are larger than the allocated header on x64, so a free-list 
operation can write into bytes that become user payload after allocation.
codex
The key is not that free-list code directly assigns `m_previous`; it can leave stale/overlapping 
`FreeBlock` metadata in an allocated block’s payload. I’m checking the remove path details so the 
cited line is precise rather than just the surrounding function.
